    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Ex's Side of the Story</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Sondra Brody letter on April 22 article about Andrew Neel's documentary about his grandmother Alice Neel; says it's unfair to attack people in Neel's life who are dead and can't fight back (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Grandson Paints a Portrait of a Portraitist'' by [April 22]:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Grandson Paints a Portrait of a Portraitist'' by [April 22]:</p>
        <p>Carol Kino wrote sympathetically of Andrew Neel's film about his painter grandmother, Alice Neel. With her fame came the chance for Neel to create an image of the vulnerable female artist triumphing after a life of abuse by men. One of the abusers always mentioned is Sam Brody. I knew Sam Brody; he was my husband for 30 years. He died 20 years ago in a tragic accident. Sam and Alice were complicated people. Is it fair to attack someone who can't fight back?</p>
        <p>Sondra Brody  Old Saybrook, Conn.</p>
        <p>ALICE NEEL</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
